[src:apt-package/apt-8-en] The apt(8) commandline is designed as an end-user tool and it may change behavior between versions.
[src:apt-package/apt-8-en] While it tries not to break backward compatibility this is not guaranteed either if a change seems beneficial for interactive use.
[src:apt-package/apt-8-en] All features of apt(8) are available in dedicated APT tools like apt-get(8) and apt-cache(8) as well. apt(8) just changes the default value of some options (see apt.conf(5) and specifically the Binary scope).
[src:apt-package/apt-8-en] So you should prefer using these commands (potentially with some additional options enabled) in your scripts as they keep backward compatibility as much as possible.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Unless the **-h**, or **--help** option is given, one of the commands below must be present.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] update is used to resynchronize the package index files from their sources.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The indexes of available packages are fetched from the location(s) specified in /etc/apt/sources.list.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] For example, when using a Debian archive, this command retrieves and scans the Packages.gz files, so that information about new and updated packages is available.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] An update should always be performed before an upgrade or dist-upgrade.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Please be aware that the overall progress meter will be incorrect as the size of the package files cannot be known in advance.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] upgrade is used to install the newest versions of all packages currently installed on the system from the sources enumerated in /etc/apt/sources.list.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Packages currently installed with new versions available are retrieved and upgraded; under no circumstances are currently installed packages removed, or packages not already installed retrieved and installed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] New versions of currently installed packages that cannot be upgraded without changing the install status of another package will be left at their current version.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] knows that new versions of packages are available.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] has a "smart" conflict resolution system, and it will attempt to upgrade the most important packages at the expense of less important ones if necessary.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The dist-upgrade command may therefore remove some packages.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The /etc/apt/sources.list file contains a list of locations from which to retrieve desired package files.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] for a mechanism for overriding the general settings for individual packages.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] to the Status field of available packages, and performs the actions necessary to realize that state (for instance, the removal of old and the installation of new packages).
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] install is followed by one or more packages desired for installation or upgrading.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Each package is a package name, not a fully qualified filename (for instance, in a Debian system, apt-utils would be the argument provided, not apt-utils_2.6.1_amd64.deb).
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] All packages required by the package(s) specified for installation will also be retrieved and installed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The /etc/apt/sources.list file is used to locate the desired packages.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] If a hyphen is appended to the package name (with no intervening space), the identified package will be removed if it is installed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Similarly a plus sign can be used to designate a package to install.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] These latter features may be used to override decisions made by apt-get's conflict resolution system.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] A specific version of a package can be selected for installation by following the package name with an equals and the version of the package to select.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] This will cause that version to be located and selected for install.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Alternatively a specific distribution can be selected by following the package name with a slash and the version of the distribution or the Archive name (stable, testing, unstable).
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Both of the version selection mechanisms can downgrade packages and must be used with care.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] This is also the target to use if you want to upgrade one or more already-installed packages without upgrading every package you have on your system.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Unlike the "upgrade" target, which installs the newest version of all currently installed packages, "install" will install the newest version of only the package(s) specified.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Simply provide the name of the package(s) you wish to upgrade, and if a newer version is available, it (and its dependencies, as described above) will be downloaded and installed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Finally, the apt_preferences(5) mechanism allows you to create an alternative installation policy for individual packages.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] If no package matches the given expression and the expression contains one of '.', '?' or '*' then it is assumed to be a POSIX regular expression, and it is applied to all package names in the database.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Any matches are then installed (or removed).
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Note that matching is done by substring so 'lo.*' matches 'how-lo' and 'lowest'.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] If this is undesired, anchor the regular expression with a '^' or '$' character, or create a more specific regular expression.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Fallback to regular expressions is deprecated in APT 2.0, has been removed in apt(8), except for anchored expressions, and will be removed from apt-get(8) in a future version.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] reinstall is an alias for install --reinstall.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] remove is identical to install except that packages are removed instead of installed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Note that removing a package leaves its configuration files on the system.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] If a plus sign is appended to the package name (with no intervening space), the identified package will be installed instead of removed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] purge is identical to remove except that packages are removed and purged (any configuration files are deleted too).
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] APT will examine the available packages to decide which source package to fetch.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] option or per package with the pkg/release syntax, if possible.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The arguments are interpreted as binary and source package names.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] See the **--only-source** option if you want to change that.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Source packages are tracked separately from binary packages via deb-src lines in the sources.list(5) file.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] This means that you will need to add such a line for each repository you want to get sources from; otherwise you will probably get either the wrong (too old/too new) source versions or none at all.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] If the **--compile** option is specified then the package will be compiled to a binary .deb using **dpkg-buildpackage** for the architecture as defined by the **--host-architecture** option.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] If **--download-only** is specified then the source package will not be unpacked.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] A specific source version can be retrieved by postfixing the source name with an equals and then the version to fetch, similar to the mechanism used for the package files.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] This enables exact matching of the source package name and version, implicitly enabling the APT::Get::Only-Source option.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Note that source packages are not installed and tracked in the **dpkg** database like binary packages; they are simply downloaded to the current directory, like source tarballs.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] build-dep causes apt-get to install/remove packages in an attempt to satisfy the build dependencies for a source package.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] By default the dependencies are satisfied to build the package natively.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The arguments are interpreted as binary or source package names.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] satisfy causes apt-get to satisfy the given dependency strings.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The dependency strings may have build profiles and architecture restriction list as in build dependencies.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] They may optionally be prefixed with "Conflicts: " to unsatisfy the dependency string.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Multiple strings of the same type can be specified.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The legacy operator '</>' is not supported, use '<=/>=' instead.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] check is a diagnostic tool; it updates the package cache and checks for broken dependencies.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] download will download the given binary package into the current directory.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The authenticity of the package data is ensured as usual.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] clean clears out the local repository of retrieved package files.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] It removes everything but the lock file from /var/cache/apt/archives/ and /var/cache/apt/archives/partial/.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Like clean, autoclean clears out the local repository of retrieved package files.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The difference is that it only removes package files that can no longer be downloaded, and are largely useless.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] This allows a cache to be maintained over a long period without it growing out of control.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The configuration option APT::Clean-Installed will prevent installed packages from being erased if it is set to off.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] autoremove is used to remove packages that were automatically installed to satisfy dependencies for other packages and are now no longer needed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Like autoremove, but autopurge also removes configuration files.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] This is a shortcut for autoremove --purge.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] By default it displays the changelog for the version that is installed.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] option to modify the output format as well as accepts lines of the default output to filter the records by.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The command is mainly used as an interface for external tools working with APT to get information as well as filenames for downloaded files so they can use them as well instead of downloading them again on their own.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Detailed documentation is omitted here and can instead be found in the file /usr/share/doc/apt/acquire-additional-files.md.gz shipped by the apt-doc package.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] All command line options may be set using the configuration file, the descriptions indicate the configuration option to set.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] For boolean options you can override the config file by using something like **-f-**,**--no-f**, **-f=no** or several other variations.
