[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Fail the update command if any error occured, even a transient one.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Configuration File; Specify a configuration file to use.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] The program will read the default configuration file and then this configuration file.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Set a Configuration Option; This will set an arbitrary configuration option.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] can be used multiple times to set different options.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Configuration Item: Dir::Etc::SourceList.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] File fragments for locations to fetch packages from.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Configuration Item: Dir::Etc::SourceParts.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] This is where you would specify "pinning", i.e. a preference to get certain packages from a separate source or from a different version of a distribution.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Configuration Item: Dir::Etc::Preferences.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] File fragments for the version preferences.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Configuration Item: Dir::Etc::PreferencesParts.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Storage area for retrieved package files.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Configuration Item: Dir::Cache::Archives.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Storage area for package files in transit.
[src:apt-package/apt-get-8-en] Storage area for state information in transit.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] APT is a collection of tools distributed in a package named *apt*.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] A significant part of APT is defined in a C++ library of functions; APT also includes command-line programs for dealing with packages, which use the library.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] Three such programs are `apt`, `apt-get` and `apt-cache`.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] They are commonly used in examples because they are simple and ubiquitous.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] The *apt* package is of "*important*" priority in all current Debian releases, and is therefore included in a default Debian installation.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] APT can be considered a front end to `dpkg`, friendlier than the older `dselect` front end.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] While `dpkg` performs actions on individual packages, APT manages relations (especially dependencies) between them, as well as sourcing and management of higher-level versioning decisions such as release tracking and Upgrade Suppression.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] APT is often hailed as one of Debian's best features, which Debian developers attribute to the strict quality controls in Debian's policy.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] A major feature of APT is the way it calls `dpkg` –it performs topological sorting of the list of packages to be installed or removed and calls `dpkg` in the best possible sequence.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] In some cases, it utilizes the `--force` options of `dpkg`.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] However, it only does this when it is unable to calculate how to avoid the reason `dpkg` requires the action to be forced.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] The user indicates one or more packages to be installed.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] Each package name is phrased as just the name portion of the package, not a fully qualified filename (for instance, in a Debian system, `libc6` would be the argument provided, not `libc6_1.9.6-2.deb`).
[src:apt-package/apt-software] Notably, APT automatically gets and installs packages upon which the indicated package depends (if necessary).
[src:apt-package/apt-software] This was an original distinguishing characteristic of APT-based package management systems, as it avoided installation failure due to missing dependencies, a type of dependency hell.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] Another distinction is the retrieval of packages from remote repositories.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] APT uses a location configuration file (`/etc/apt/sources.list`) to locate the desired packages, which might be available on the network or a removable storage medium, for example, and retrieve them, and also obtain information about available (but not installed) packages.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] APT provides other command options to override decisions made by apt-get's conflict resolution system.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] One option is to force a particular version of a package.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] This can downgrade a package and render dependent software inoperable, so the user must be careful.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] Finally, the `apt_preferences` mechanism allows the user to create an alternative installation policy for individual packages.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] The user can specify packages using a POSIX regular expression.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] APT searches its cached list of packages and lists the dependencies that must be installed or updated.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] APT retrieves, configures and installs the dependencies automatically.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] Triggers are the treatment of deferred actions.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] `/etc/apt` contains the APT configuration folders and files.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] `apt-config` is the APT Configuration Query program.
[src:apt-package/apt-software] `apt-config dump` shows the configuration.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It is deployed across servers, personal computers, and embedded devices.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Among Linux distributions, it ranks second only to Ubuntu (which is itself derived from Debian), with 16% of the overall market.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] According to the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 11.4% of developers use it as their primary personal operating system and 10.4% professionally.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Its emphasis on stability and long-term support over frequent package updates has made it prevalent in server and embedded deployments.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Development is led by the Project Leader and guided by two foundational documents: the Debian Social Contract, a summary of the project's commitments that includes the Debian Free Software Guidelines (DFSG), and the Debian Constitution, which describes the organizational structure.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The project publishes three concurrent development branches: stable, testing, and unstable, which correspond to different levels of software maturity.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The current stable release, "Trixie", released on August 9, 2025, includes tens of thousands of packages maintained by more than a thousand active contributors.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Since 1997, the project has operated independently through Software in the Public Interest (SPI), a non-profit corporation founded by project members to hold its assets and trademarks.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It previously received support from the Free Software Foundation (FSF) between 1994 and 1995, a sponsorship that ended due to disagreements.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian uses version numbers and code names based on the characters of the *Toy Story* franchise to refer to its releases.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] This naming convention was introduced by former project leader Bruce Perens, who was working at Pixar at the time.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The unstable branch is permanently named after Sid, the neighborhood child known for destroying toys.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The first public mention of the project occurred on August 16, 1993, when Ian Murdock posted an announcement to the *comp.os.linux.development* newsgroup.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Murdock founded the project due to his dissatisfaction with the Softlanding Linux System (SLS); after making extensive modifications to this system, he concluded that it would be more efficient to develop a new distribution from scratch.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Similar to the original announcement of Linux, Murdock's post solicited feedback and suggestions on how the system could be improved.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The name *Debian* was a portmanteau of his first name and that of his then-wife, Deborah Lynn.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The first internal release, pre-alpha 0.01, came out on September 15, 1993.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The first public versions, beta 0.90 and beta 0.91, followed on January 26 and 29, 1994, respectively, with their mailing lists hosted by Pixar.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] These releases included the Debian Linux Manifesto, in which Murdock outlined his vision for the project, advocating for a distribution "developed openly in the spirit of Linux and GNU".
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Between November 1994 and November 1995, the project was sponsored by the FSF, whose sponsorship Murdock had sought with the hope that it would also give the FSF experience in packaging a complete GNU system.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In March 1995, Murdock stepped down as project leader to dedicate more time to his studies, work, and family; the new team did not seek to continue the FSF sponsorship.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Following the end of that sponsorship, Debian motivated the formation of Software in the Public Interest (SPI), a non-profit corporation registered in the state of New York.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] SPI was founded to help Debian and other similar organizations develop and distribute open hardware and software, acting as a fiscal sponsor by handling non-technical administrative tasks so that projects are not required to operate their own legal entity.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In April 1996, Bruce Perens became the project leader.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On June 17 of the same year, Debian 1.1 "Buzz" was released, the first release under his leadership.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] By that time, Ian Jackson's dpkg had already become an integral part of Debian.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] He created BusyBox to enable running the installer from a single floppy disk.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] By the time Debian 1.2 "Rex" was released on December 12, 1996, the project had grown to nearly 200 volunteers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Perens stepped down as project leader in December 1997 and left the project entirely on March 18, 1998.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Ian Jackson became project leader in January 1998.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 2.0 "Hamm", released on July 24, 1998, was the first multi-architecture release of Debian, adding support for the Motorola 68000 family (m68k).
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On December 2, 1998, the Debian Constitution was ratified for the first time, simultaneously initiating the election process that would result in Wichert Akkerman succeeding Jackson as project leader in January 1999.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On March 9, 1999, Debian 2.1 "Slink" was released, alongside the package manager front-end APT.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On May 23, 1999, the Internal Revenue Service determined that SPI qualifies for 501(c)(3) status, providing a mechanism by which the Debian Project may accept contributions that are tax deductible in the United States.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On December 13, 2000, Debian activated package pools on its ftp-master archive server, a change to the archive system that had to be made before preparation of the "Woody" release could begin.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A package pool consists of a collection of different versions of a given package, from which branches, experimental, unstable, testing, and stable, draw packages for inclusion in their respective package files.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] This change enabled special-purpose distributions, including a new testing branch that was used for the first time to prepare "Woody" for release.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Under this system, packages from unstable considered to be sufficiently stable were promoted to testing after a waiting period of several weeks, a mechanism intended to reduce freeze time and allow the project to prepare a new release at any point.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The first Debian Conference was held in Bordeaux, France, from July 5 to 9, 2000.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The event brought Debian developers and advanced users together in person for the first time, giving the Debian project a physical presence as an organization rather than existing solely as an online collective.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In addition to working sessions, the conference served as a venue for attendees to meet other members of the free software community, with some presentations open to the general public.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The program combined presentations, technical talks, birds-of-a-feather sessions, and coding parties.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In May 2001, Hewlett-Packard (HP) announced that it would use Debian as the basis for its future Linux development work.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian developer Bruce Perens, who acted as HP's Linux advocate, disclosed the decision in an email to the Debian development mailing list, noting that HP had already begun distributing Debian to customers and planned to offer support and training for it.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Perens described the move as an initial step toward HP's broader support for the Linux Standard Base (LSB) project.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On November 20, 2002, a fire destroyed the network operations center at the University of Twente in the Netherlands, which hosted one of Debian's servers, satie.debian.org.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The blaze broke out around 8:00 a.m. local time and consumed the building so thoroughly that firefighters could not save the server room.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Because satie had hosted the project's security archive, its non-US archive, and the databases supporting new-maintainer applications and quality assurance, the corresponding services (security.debian.org, non-us.debian.org, nm.debian.org, and qa.debian.org) went offline as a result.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian subsequently rebuilt these services on another host, klecker, which had recently been relocated from the United States to the Netherlands.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Released on July 19, 2002, Debian 3.0 "Woody" expanded the project's scope.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Supported by a community of over 900 developers and led by newly appointed Project Leader Bdale Garbee, the release included approximately 8,500 binary packages distributed across seven official binary CDs.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] This version broadened hardware compatibility by introducing support for several new architectures, including IA-64, HP PA-RISC, MIPS (both big and little endian), and S/390.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Furthermore, it was the first Debian release to incorporate cryptographic software, following the relaxation of Cold War US cryptography export restrictions, as well as the first to feature the KDE desktop environment after its Qt licensing issues were resolved.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On October 20, 2004, Mark Shuttleworth announced the first release of Ubuntu, 4.10 "Warty Warthog", a new Debian-derived distribution aimed at combining Debian's extensive package base with a faster installer, a fixed six-month release cycle, and 18 months of security support per release.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The rapid growth of Ubuntu sparked debate within the Debian community regarding the long-term compatibility of Debian-derived distributions.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Some Debian developers warned that as more developers began building packages targeting Ubuntu rather than Debian proper, divergence between the two could erode that compatibility, mimicking the fragmentation seen among RPM-based distributions.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Other community members argued that Debian should address its lengthy release cycles, calling for a predictable, time-based release schedule similar to that adopted by the GNOME Project, in order to reduce the incentive for downstream distributions to fork.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The 3.1 Sarge release was made in June 2005.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] This release updated 73% of the software and included over 9,000 new packages.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] An installation manual and release notes were in ten and fifteen languages respectively.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The efforts of Skolelinux, Debian-Med and Debian-Accessibility raised the number of packages that were educational or had a medical affiliation, and of packages made for people with disabilities.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In 2006, as a result of a much-publicized dispute, Mozilla software was rebranded in Debian.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Mozilla Corporation stated that software with unapproved modifications could not be distributed under the Firefox trademark.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Two reasons that Debian had modified the Firefox software were to replace non-free artwork and to provide security patches.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Consequently, Debian contained a fork of Firefox named Iceweasel and one of Thunderbird named Icedove.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In February 2016, it was announced that Mozilla and Debian had reached an agreement and Iceweasel would revert to the name Firefox; a similar agreement was anticipated for Icedove/Thunderbird.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A fundraising experiment, Dunc-Tank, was created to solve the release cycle problem and release managers were paid to work full-time; in response, unpaid developers slowed down their work and the release was delayed.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 4.0 (Etch) was released in April 2007, featuring the x86-64 port and a graphical installer.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 5.0 (Lenny) was released in February 2009, supporting Marvell's Orion platform and netbooks such as the Asus Eee PC.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The release was dedicated to Thiemo Seufer, a developer who died in a car crash.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In July 2009, the policy of time-based development freezes on a two-year cycle was announced.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Time-based freezes are intended to blend the predictability of time based releases with Debian's policy of feature-based releases, and to reduce overall freeze time.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Squeeze cycle was going to be especially short; however, this initial schedule was abandoned.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In September 2010, the backporting service became official, providing more recent versions of some software for the stable release.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 6.0 (Squeeze) was released in February 2011, featuring Debian GNU/kFreeBSD as a technology preview, along with adding a dependency-based boot system, and moving problematic firmware to the non-free section.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 7 (Wheezy) was released in May 2013, featuring multiarch support.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 8 (Jessie) was released in April 2015, using systemd as the new init system.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 9 (Stretch) was released in June 2017, with nftables as a replacement for iptables, support for Flatpak apps, and MariaDB as the replacement for MySQL.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian was formerly released as a very large set of CDs for each architecture, but with the release of Debian 9 (Stretch) in 2017, many of the images have been dropped from the archive but remain buildable via jigdo.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 10 (Buster) was released in July 2019, adding support for Secure Boot and enabling AppArmor by default.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 11 (Bullseye) was released in August 2021, enabling persistency in the system journal, adding support for driverless scanning, and containing kernel-level support for exFAT filesystems.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 12 (Bookworm) was released on June 10, 2023, including various improvements and features, increasing the supported Linux kernel to version 6.1, and leveraging new "Emerald" artwork.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 12 also was the first version under a revised Debian Social Contract that includes non-free firmware in its installation media by default, if and when the installer detects that it is needed for installed hardware to function, such as with Wi-Fi cards.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 13 (Trixie) was released on August 9, 2025.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 14 has been announced to have the code name Forky, and Debian 15 has been announced to have the code name Duke.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian is under continuous development and new packages are uploaded to *unstable* every day.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Throughout Debian's lifetime, both the Debian distribution and its website have won various awards from different organizations, including Server Distribution of the Year 2011, The best Linux distro of 2011, and a *Best of the Net* award for October 1998.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] On December 2, 2015, Microsoft announced that they would offer Debian as an endorsed distribution on the Azure cloud platform.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian has also been made available for installation in Microsoft's Windows Subsystem for Linux, which allows a user to install a tightly integrated Debian virtual machine within Windows.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian has online repositories that contain nearly 70,000 packages for the stable release.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian officially contains only free software, but non-free software can be downloaded and installed from the Debian repositories.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian includes popular free programs such as LibreOffice, Firefox web browser, Thunderbird e-mail client, VLC media player, GIMP image editor, and Okular document viewer.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian is a popular choice for servers, for example as the operating system component of a LAMP stack.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Beyond the typical server environment, Debian is increasingly used in cloud computing, containerization, and artificial intelligence (AI) development.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It serves as a foundation for Docker containers and is supported by Google Cloud's deep learning virtual machines (VMs), positioning it as a platform for new workloads.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Several flavors of the Linux kernel exist for each port.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] For example, the i386 port has flavors for IA-32 PCs supporting Physical Address Extension and real-time computing, for older PCs, and for x86-64 PCs.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Linux kernel does not officially contain firmware lacking source code, although such firmware is available in non-free packages and alternative installation media.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Many desktop environments are available in the project's main repository.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] GNOME (the default in the installer) and KDE Plasma are the most widely installed according to the Debian Popularity Contest.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Other environments are also available, such as Xfce, LXDE, LXQt, MATE, and Lumina.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Standalone X11 window managers and Wayland compositors are also included, such as Openbox, Fluxbox, Compiz, awesome, i3, dwm, Notion, Sway, and wmii.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Several parts of Debian are translated into languages other than American English, including package descriptions, configuration messages, documentation and the website.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The level of software localization depends on the language, ranging from the highly supported German and French to the barely translated Creek and Samoan.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Debian 10 installer is available in 76 languages.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Multimedia support has been problematic in Debian regarding codecs threatened by possible patent infringements, lacking source code, or under too restrictive licenses.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Even though packages with problems related to their distribution could go into the non-free area, software such as libdvdcss is not hosted at Debian .
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian offers DVD and CD images for installation that can be downloaded using HTTP, FTP, BitTorrent or jigdo.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Physical discs can also be bought from retailers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The full sets are made up of several discs (the amd64 port consists of 13 DVDs or 84 CDs), but only the first disc is required for installation, as the installer can retrieve software not contained in the first disc image from online repositories.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian offers different network installation methods.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A minimal install of Debian is available via the *netinst* CD, whereby Debian is installed with just a base and later added software can be downloaded from the Internet.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Another option is to boot the installer from the network.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The default bootstrap loader is GNU GRUB version 2, though the package name is simply grub, while version 1 was renamed to grub-legacy.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] This conflicts with distros (e.g., Fedora Linux), where grub version 2 is named grub2.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The default desktop may be chosen from the DVD boot menu among GNOME, KDE Plasma, Xfce, LXDE, and LXQt and from special disc 1 CDs.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian releases live install images for CDs, DVDs and USB flash drives for x86-64 architecture, and with a choice of desktop environments.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] These *Debian Live* images allow users to boot from removable media and run Debian without affecting the contents of their computer.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A full install of Debian to the computer's hard drive can be initiated from the live image environment.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Personalized images can be built with the live-build tool for discs, USB drives and for network booting purposes.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Installation images are hybrid on some architectures and can be used to create a bootable USB drive (Live USB).
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Package management operations can be performed with different tools available on Debian, from the lowest level command dpkg to graphical front-ends like Synaptic.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The recommended standard for administering packages on a Debian system is the apt toolset.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] dpkg provides the low-level infrastructure for package management.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The dpkg database contains the list of installed software on the current system.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The dpkg command tool does not know about repositories.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] These can be either under the dpkg database directory tree or in arbitrary locations specified by the user.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] An Advanced Packaging Tool (APT) allows a Debian system to retrieve and resolve package dependencies from repositories.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] APT tools share dependency information and cached packages.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] GDebi is an APT tool which can be used in command-line and on the GUI.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] GDebi can install a local .deb file via the command line like the dpkg command, but with access to repositories to resolve dependencies.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Other graphical front-ends for APT include Software Center, Synaptic and Apper.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] GNOME Software is a graphical front-end for PackageKit, which can work on various software packaging systems.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Debian Free Software Guidelines (DFSG) define the distinctive meaning of the word "free" as in "free and open-source software".
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Packages that comply with these guidelines, usually under the GNU General Public License, Modified BSD License or Artistic License, are included inside the *main* area; otherwise, they are included inside the *non-free* and *contrib* areas.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] These last two areas are not distributed within the official installation media, but they can be adopted manually.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Non-free includes packages that do not comply with the DFSG, such as documentation with invariant sections and proprietary software, and legally questionable packages.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Contrib includes packages which do comply with the DFSG but fail other requirements.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] For example, they may depend on packages which are in non-free or requires such for building them.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Richard Stallman and the Free Software Foundation have criticized the Debian project for hosting the non-free repository and because the contrib and non-free areas are easily accessible, an opinion echoed by some in Debian including the former project leader Wichert Akkerman.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The internal dissent in the Debian project regarding the non-free section has persisted, but the last time it came to a vote in 2004, the majority voted to keep it.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The most popular optional Linux cross-distribution package manager are graphical (front-ends) package managers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] They are available within the official Debian Repository but are not installed by default.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] They are widely popular with both Debian users and Debian software developers who are interested in installing the most recent versions of application or using the cross-distribution package manager built-in sandbox environment.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] While at the same time remaining in control of the security.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The *snapshot* archive provides older versions of the branches.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] They may be used to install a specific older version of some software.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The numbering scheme for the point releases up to Debian 4.0 was to include the letter *r* (for *revision*) after the main version number and then the number of the point release; for example, the latest point release of version 4.0 is 4.0r9.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] This scheme was chosen because a new dotted version would make the old one look obsolete and vendors would have trouble selling their CDs.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] From Debian 5.0, the numbering scheme of point releases was changed, conforming to the GNU version numbering standard; the first point release of Debian 5.0 was 5.0.1 instead of 5.0r1.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The numbering scheme was once again changed for the first Debian 7 update, which was version 7.1.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The *r* scheme is no longer in use, but point release announcements include a note about not throwing away old installation media.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The official logo (also known as *open use logo*) contains the well-known Debian *swirl* and best represents the visual identity of the Debian Project.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A separate logo also exists for use by the Debian Project and its members only.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Debian "swirl" logo was designed by Raul Silva in 1999 as part of a contest to replace the semi-official logo that had been used.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The winner of the contest received an @Debian.org email address, and a set of Debian 2.1 install CDs for the architecture of their choice.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] There has been no official statement from the Debian project on the logo's meaning, but at the time of the logo's selection, it was suggested that the logo represented the magic smoke that made computers work.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] One theory about the origin of the Debian logo is that Buzz Lightyear, the chosen character for the first named Debian release, has a swirl in his chin.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Stefano Zacchiroli also suggested that this swirl is the Debian one.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Buzz Lightyear's swirl is a more likely candidate as the codenames for Debian are names of Toy Story characters.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The former Debian project leader Bruce Perens used to work for Pixar and is credited as a studio tools engineer on *Toy Story 2* (1999).
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Hardware requirements are at least those of the kernel and the GNU toolsets.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The real minimum memory requirements depend on the architecture and may be much less than the numbers listed in this table.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It is possible to install Debian with 170 MB of RAM for x86-64; the installer will run in low memory mode and it is recommended to create a swap partition.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The installer for z/Architecture requires about 20 MB of RAM, but relies on network hardware.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Similarly, disk space requirements, which depend on the packages to be installed, can be reduced by manually selecting the packages needed.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] As of May 2019, no Pure Blend exists that would lower the hardware requirements easily.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It is possible to run graphical user interfaces on older or low-end systems.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] However, installing window managers instead of desktop environments is recommended, as desktop environments use more resources.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Requirements for individual software vary widely and must be considered, with those of the base operating environment.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian supports a variety of ARM-based network-attached storage (NAS) devices.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The NSLU2 was supported by the installer in Debian 4.0 and 5.0, and Martin Michlmayr is providing installation tarballs since version 6.0.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Other supported NAS devices are the Buffalo Kurobox Pro, GLAN Tank, Thecus N2100 and QNAP Turbo Stations.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Devices based on the Kirkwood system on a chip (SoC) are supported too, such as the SheevaPlug plug computer and OpenRD products.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] There are efforts to run Debian on mobile devices, but this is not a project goal yet since the Debian Linux kernel maintainers would not apply the needed patches.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Nevertheless, packages exist for resource-limited systems.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] There are efforts to support Debian on wireless access points.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian is known to run on set-top boxes.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Work is ongoing to support the AM335x processor, which is used in electronic point of service solutions.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian may be customized to run on cash machines.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] BeagleBoard, a low-power open-source hardware single-board computer made by Texas Instruments, has switched to Debian Linux preloaded on its Beaglebone Black board's flash.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Roqos Core, a x86-64 based IPS firewall router, runs on Debian Linux.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian's policies and team efforts focus on collaborative software development and testing processes.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] As a result, a new major release tends to occur every two years with revision releases that fix security issues and important problems.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian developers are organized in a web of trust.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] There are at present about one thousand active Debian developers, but it is possible to contribute to the project without being an official developer.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The project maintains official mailing lists and conferences for communication and coordination between developers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] For issues with single packages and other tasks, a public bug tracking system is used by developers and end users.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Internet Relay Chat is also used for communication among developers and to provide real time help.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian is supported by donations made to organizations authorized by the leader.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The largest supporter is Software in the Public Interest, the owner of the Debian trademark, manager of the monetary donations and umbrella organization for various other community free software projects.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A Project Leader is elected once per year by the developers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The leader has special powers, but they are not absolute, and appoints delegates to perform specialized tasks.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Delegates make decisions as they think is best, taking into account technical criteria and consensus.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] By way of a General Resolution, the developers may recall the leader, reverse a decision made by the leader or a delegate, amend foundation documents and make other binding decisions.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The voting method is based on the Schulze method (Cloneproof Schwartz Sequential Dropping).
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Project leadership is distributed occasionally.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Branden Robinson was helped by the Project Scud, a team of developers that assisted the leader, but there were concerns that such leadership would split Debian into two developer classes.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Anthony Towns created a supplemental position, Second In Charge (2IC), that shared some powers of the leader.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Steve McIntyre was 2IC and had a 2IC himself.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] One important role in Debian's leadership is that of a release manager.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The release team sets goals for the next release, supervises the processes and decides when to release.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The team is led by the next release managers and stable release managers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Release assistants were introduced in 2003.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Debian Project has an influx of applicants wishing to become developers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] These applicants must undergo a vetting process which establishes their identity, motivation, understanding of the project's principles, and technical competence.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] This process has become much harder throughout the years.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian developers join the project for many reasons.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian developers may resign their position at any time, or when deemed necessary, they can be expelled.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Those who follow the retiring protocol are granted *emeritus* status and may regain their membership via a shortened new member process.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian has made efforts to diversify and have members represented from the community.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian Women in 2004 was established with the aim of having more women involved in development.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian also partnered with Outreachy, which offers internships to individuals with underrepresented identities in technology.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Each software package has a *maintainer* that may be either one person or a team of Debian developers and non-developer maintainers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The maintainer keeps track of upstream releases, and ensures that the package coheres with the rest of the distribution and meets the standards of quality of Debian.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Packages may include modifications introduced by Debian to achieve compliance with Debian Policy, even to fix non-Debian specific bugs, although coordination with upstream developers is advised.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The maintainer releases a new version by uploading the package to the "incoming" system, which verifies the integrity of the packages and their digital signatures.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] If the package is found to be valid, it is installed in the package archive into an area called the *pool* and distributed every day to hundreds of mirrors worldwide.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] As of April 5, 2025, there were a total of 379 Debian mirrors operating.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The upload must be signed using OpenPGP-compatible software.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] All Debian developers have individual cryptographic key pairs.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Developers are responsible for any package they upload even if the packaging was prepared by another contributor.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Initially, an accepted package is only available in the *unstable* branch.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Thus, a release-critical bug in a new version of a shared library on which many packages depend may prevent those packages from entering *Testing*, because the updated library must meet the requirements too.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] From the branch viewpoint, the migration process happens twice per day, rendering *Testing* in perpetual beta.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Periodically, the release team publishes guidelines to the developers in order to ready the release.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A new release occurs after a freeze, when all important software is reasonably up-to-date in the *Testing* branch and any other significant issues are solved.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] At that time, all packages in the *testing* branch become the new *stable* branch.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Although freeze dates are time-based, release dates are not, which are announced by the release managers a couple of weeks beforehand.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A version of a package can belong to more than one branch, usually *testing* and *unstable*.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It is possible for a package to keep the same version between stable releases and be part of *oldstable*, *stable*, *testing* and *unstable* at the same time.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Each branch can be seen as a collection of pointers into the package "pool" mentioned above.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] One way to resolve the challenge of a release-critical bug in a new application version is the use of optional package managers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] They allow software developers to use sandbox environments, while at the same time remaining in control of security.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Another benefit of a cross-distribution package manager is that they allow application developers to directly provide updates to users without going through distributions, and without having to package and test the application separately for each distribution.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] A new *stable* branch of Debian is released about every 2 years.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It will receive official support for about 3 years with update for major security or usability fixes.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Point releases will be available every several months as determined by Stable Release Managers (SRM).
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian also launched its Long Term Support (LTS) project since Debian 6 (Debian Squeeze).
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] For each Debian release, it will receive two years of extra security updates provided by LTS Team after its End Of Life (EOL).
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] However, no point releases will be made.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Now each Debian release can receive 5 years of security support in total.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Debian project handles security through public disclosure.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian security advisories are compatible with the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures dictionary, are usually coordinated with other free software vendors and are published the same day a vulnerability is made public.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] There used to be a security audit project that focused on packages in the stable release looking for security bugs; Steve Kemp, who started the project, retired in 2011 but resumed his activities and applied to rejoin in 2014.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The *stable* branch is supported by the Debian security team; *oldstable* is supported for one year.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Although Squeeze was not officially supported, Debian coordinated an effort to provide long-term support for IA-32 and x86-64 platforms, until February 2016, five years after the initial release.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] *Testing* is supported by the *testing* security team, but does not receive updates in as timely a manner as *stable*.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] *Unstable*'s security is left for the package maintainers.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The Debian project offers documentation and tools to harden a Debian installation both manually and automatically.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] AppArmor support is available and enabled by default since Buster.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian provides an optional hardening wrapper, and does not harden all of its software by default using gcc features such as PIE and buffer overflow protection, unlike operating systems such as OpenBSD, but tries to build as many packages as possible with hardening flags.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In May 2008, a Debian developer discovered that the OpenSSL package distributed with Debian and derivatives such as Ubuntu made a variety of security keys vulnerable to a random number generator attack, since only 32,767 different keys were generated.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The security weakness was caused by changes made in 2006 by another Debian developer in response to memory debugger warnings.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The complete resolution procedure was cumbersome because patching the security hole was not enough; it involved regenerating all affected keys and certificates.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Recent versions of Debian have focused more on safer defaults.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian 10 had AppArmor enabled by default, and Debian 11 improved Secure Boot support and included persistent system journaling.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The project is also making all packages reproducible, which helps to ensure software integrity.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] The cost of developing all of the packages included in Debian 5.0 Lenny (323 million lines of code) has been estimated to be about US$8 billion, using one method based on the COCOMO model.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] As of May 2024, Black Duck Open Hub estimated that the current codebase (74 million lines of code) would cost about US$1.6 billion to develop, using a different method based on the same model.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian is used by several institutions, such as many universities, NGOs and other non-profit organizations (including the Wikimedia Foundation), and commercial companies.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] It has even been used in space, in laptops on board the International Space Station.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Debian has been very helpful to numerous government agencies in the public sector, such as in the city of Munich, which used a Debian-based distribution in its LiMux initiative for the government computer migration to Linux.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] Schools in Extremadura and Andalusia (Spain) also utilized Debian-based systems (gnuLinEx and Guadalinex, respectively) to develop digital skills and open-source computing in schools.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] There are many other cases of usage of Debian-based distributions in education, such as the deployment of Skolelinux/Debian Edu in Norwegian schools.
[src:apt-package/debian-p01] In addition, other public administrations use Linux systems indirectly based on Debian, such as French Gendarmerie, which uses Ubuntu-derived GendBuntu distribution.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian is one of the most popular Linux distributions, and many other distributions have been created from the Debian codebase.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] As of 2025, DistroWatch lists 141 active Debian derivatives.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The Debian project provides its derivatives with guidelines for best practices and encourages derivatives to merge their work back into Debian.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The Linux Mint Debian Edition (LMDE) has used Debian Stable as the software source base since 2014.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian Pure Blends are subsets of a Debian release configured out-of-the-box for users with particular skills and interests.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] For example, Debian Jr. is made for children, while Debian Science is for researchers and scientists.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The complete Debian distribution includes all available Debian Pure Blends.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] "Debian Blend" (without "Pure") is a term for a Debian-based distribution that strives to become part of mainstream Debian, and have its extra features included in future releases.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian GNU/Hurd is a flavor based on the Hurd kernel (which, in turn, runs on the GNU Mach microkernel), instead of the Linux kernel.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian GNU/Hurd has been in development since 1998, and made a formal release in May 2013, with 78% of the software packaged for Debian ported to the GNU Hurd.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Hurd is not yet an official Debian release, and is maintained and developed as an unofficial port.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian GNU/Hurd is distributed as an installer CD (running the official Debian installer) or ready-to-run virtual disk image (Live CD, Live USB).
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The CD uses the IA-32 architecture, making it compatible with IA-32 and x86-64 PCs.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The current version of Debian GNU/Hurd is 2025, published in August 2025.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian GNU/kFreeBSD is a discontinued Debian flavor.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] It used the FreeBSD kernel and GNU userland.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The majority of software in Debian GNU/kFreeBSD was built from the same sources as Debian, with some kernel packages from FreeBSD.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The *k* in *kFreeBSD* is an abbreviation for *kernel*, which refers to the FreeBSD kernel.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Before discontinuing the project, Debian maintained i386 and amd64 ports.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] The last version of Debian kFreeBSD was Debian 8 (Jessie) RC3.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian GNU/kFreeBSD was created in 2002.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] It was included in Debian 6.0 (Squeeze) as a technology preview, and in Debian 7 (Wheezy) as an official port.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian GNU/kFreeBSD was discontinued as an officially supported platform as of Debian 8.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] Debian developers cited OSS, pf, jails, NDIS, and ZFS as reasons for being interested in the FreeBSD kernel.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] It has not been officially updated since Debian 8.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] However, starting in July 2019, the operating system continued to be maintained unofficially.
[src:apt-package/debian-p02] As of July 2023, the development of Debian GNU/kFreeBSD has officially terminated due to the lack of interest and developers.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:apt-package/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:apt-package/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The source list /etc/apt/sources.list and the files contained in /etc/apt/sources.list.d/ are designed to support any number of active sources and a variety of source media.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The files list one source per line (one-line style) or contain multiline stanzas defining one or more sources per stanza (deb822 style), with the most preferred source listed first (in case a single version is available from more than one source).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The information available from the configured sources is acquired by **apt-get update** (or by an equivalent command from another APT front-end).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The /etc/apt/sources.list.d directory provides a way to add sources.list entries in separate files.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Two different file formats are allowed as described in the next two sections.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Filenames need to have either the extension .list or .sources depending on the contained format.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The filenames may only contain letters (a-z and A-Z), digits (0-9), underscore (_), hyphen (-) and period (.) characters.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Otherwise APT will print a notice that it has ignored a file, unless that file matches a pattern in the Dir::Ignore-Files-Silently configuration list - in which case it will be silently ignored.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Files in this format have the extension .list.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Each line specifying a source starts with a type (e.g. deb-src) followed by options and arguments for this type.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Individual entries cannot be continued onto a following line.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Empty lines are ignored, and a # character anywhere on a line marks the remainder of that line as a comment.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Consequently an entry can be disabled by commenting out the entire line.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] If options should be provided they are separated by spaces and all of them together are enclosed by square brackets ([]) included in the line after the type separated from it with a space.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] If an option allows multiple values these are separated from each other with a comma (,).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] An option name is separated from its value(s) by an equals sign (=).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Multivalue options also have -= and += as separators, which instead of replacing the default with the given value(s) modify the default value(s) to remove or include the given values.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] This is the traditional format and supported by all apt versions.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Note that not all options as described below are supported by all apt versions.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Note also that some older applications parsing this format on their own might not expect to encounter options as they were uncommon before the introduction of multi-architecture support.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Files in this format have the extension .sources.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The format is similar in syntax to other files used by Debian and its derivatives, such as the metadata files that apt will download from the configured sources or the debian/control file in a Debian source package.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Individual entries are separated by an empty line; additional empty lines are ignored, and a # character at the start of the line marks the entire line as a comment.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] An entry can hence be disabled by commenting out each line belonging to the stanza, but it is usually easier to add the field "Enabled: no" to the stanza to disable the entry.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Removing the field or setting it to yes re-enables it.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Options have the same syntax as every other field: A field name separated by a colon (:) and optionally spaces from its value(s).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Note especially that multiple values are separated by whitespaces (like spaces, tabs and newlines), not by commas as in the one-line format.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Multivalue fields like Architectures also have Architectures-Add and Architectures-Remove to modify the default value rather than replacing it.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] This is a new format supported by apt itself since version 1.1.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Previous versions ignore such files with a notice message as described earlier.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] It is intended to make this format gradually the default format, deprecating the previously described one-line-style format, as it is easier to create, extend and modify for humans and machines alike especially if a lot of sources and/or options are involved.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Developers who are working with and/or parsing apt sources are highly encouraged to add support for this format and to contact the APT team to coordinate and share this work.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Users can freely adopt this format already, but may encounter problems with software not supporting the format yet.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The deb type references a typical two-level Debian archive, distribution/component.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The distribution is generally a suite name like stable or testing or a codename like bookworm or trixie while component is one of main, contrib, non-free or non-free-firmware.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The deb-src type references a Debian distribution's source code in the same form as the deb type.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] A deb-src line is required to fetch source indexes.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The URI for the deb type must specify the base of the Debian distribution, from which APT will find the information it needs. suite can specify an exact path, in which case the components must be omitted and suite must end with a slash (/).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] This is useful for the case when only a particular sub-directory of the archive denoted by the URI is of interest.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] If suite does not specify an exact path, at least one component must be present.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] suite may also contain a variable, $(ARCH) which expands to the Debian architecture (such as amd64 or armel) used on the system.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] This permits architecture-independent sources.list files to be used.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] In general this is only of interest when specifying an exact path; APT will automatically generate a URI with the current architecture otherwise.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Especially in the one-line-style format since only one distribution can be specified per line it may be necessary to have multiple lines for the same URI, if a subset of all available distributions or components at that location is desired.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] APT also parallelizes connections to different hosts to more effectively deal with sites with low bandwidth.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] It is important to list sources in order of preference, with the most preferred source listed first.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Typically this will result in sorting by speed from fastest to slowest (CD-ROM followed by hosts on a local network, followed by distant Internet hosts, for example).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Each source entry can have options specified to modify which source is accessed and how data is acquired from it.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Format, syntax and names of the options vary between the one-line-style and deb822-style formats as described, but they both have the same options available.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] For simplicity we list the deb822 field name and provide the one-line name in brackets.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Remember that besides setting multivalue options explicitly, there is also the option to modify them based on the default, but we aren't listing those names explicitly here.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Unsupported options are silently ignored by all APT versions.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) is a multivalue option defining for which architectures information should be downloaded.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) is a multivalue option defining for which languages information such as translated package descriptions should be downloaded.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) is a multivalue option defining which download targets apt will try to acquire from this source.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] configuration scope (targets are specified by their name in the Created-By field).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Additionally, targets can be enabled or disabled by using the Identifier field as an option with a boolean value instead of using this multivalue option.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) is a yes/no value which controls if APT should try to use PDiffs to update old indexes instead of downloading the new indexes entirely.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The value of this option is ignored if the repository doesn't announce the availability of PDiffs.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) can have the value yes, no or force and controls if APT should try to acquire indexes via a URI constructed from a hashsum of the expected file instead of using the well-known stable filename of the index.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Using this can avoid hashsum mismatches, but requires a supporting mirror.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] A yes or no value activates/disables the use of this feature if this source indicates support for it, while force will enable the feature regardless of what the source indicates.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Furthermore, there are options which if set affect *all* sources with the same URI and Suite, so they have to be set on all such entries and can not be varied between different components.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] APT will try to detect and error out on such anomalies.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) are boolean values which all default to no.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] and should therefore not be used lightly!
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) is a tri-state value which defaults to APT deciding if a source is considered trusted or if warnings should be raised before e.g. packages are installed from this source.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] This option can be used to override that decision.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The value yes tells APT always to consider this source as trusted, even if it doesn't pass authentication checks.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] , and should therefore only be used in a local and trusted context (if at all) as otherwise security is breached.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The value no does the opposite, causing the source to be handled as untrusted even if the authentication checks passed successfully.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The default value can't be set explicitly.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] verification with a certain set of keys rather than all trusted keys apt has configured.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] It is specified as a list of absolute paths to keyring files (have to be accessible and readable for the _apt system user, so ensure everyone has read-permissions on the file) and fingerprints of keys to select from these keyrings.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The recommended locations for keyrings are /usr/share/keyrings for keyrings managed by packages, and /etc/apt/keyrings for keyrings managed by the system operator.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] If no fingerprint is specified all keys in the keyrings are selected.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] A fingerprint will accept also all signatures by a subkey of this key, if this isn't desired an exclamation mark (!) can be appended to the fingerprint to disable this behaviour.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The option defaults to the value of the option with the same name if set in the previously acquired Release file of this repository (only fingerprints can be specified there through).
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Otherwise all keys in the trusted keyrings are considered valid signers for this repository.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The option may also be set directly to an embedded GPG public key block.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) is a yes/no value which controls if APT should try to detect replay attacks.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] A repository creator can declare a time until which the data provided in the repository should be considered valid, and if this time is reached, but no new data is provided, the data is considered expired and an error is raised.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Besides increasing security, as a malicious attacker can't send old data forever to prevent a user from upgrading to a new version, this also helps users identify mirrors which are no longer updated.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] However, some repositories such as historic archives are not updated any more by design, so this check can be disabled by setting this option to no.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) is a yes/no value which controls if APT should consider the machine's time correct and hence perform time related checks, such as verifying that a Release file is not from the future.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) controls how far from the future a repository may be.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] ) determines the path to the InRelease file, relative to the normal position of an InRelease file.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] By default, this option is unset and APT will try to fetch an InRelease or, if that fails, a Release file and its associated Release.gpg file.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] By setting this option, the specified path will be tried instead of the InRelease file, and the fallback to Release files will be disabled.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The http scheme specifies an HTTP server for an archive and is the most commonly used method.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Note that these forms of authentication are insecure as the whole communication with the remote server (or proxy) is not encrypted so a sufficiently capable attacker can observe and record login as well as all other interactions.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The attacker can *not* modify the communication through as APT's data security model is independent of the chosen transport method.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The https scheme specifies an HTTPS server for an archive and is very similar in use and available options to the http scheme.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The main difference is that the communication between apt and server (or proxy) is encrypted.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Note that the encryption does not prevent an attacker from knowing which server (or proxy) apt is communicating with and deeper analysis can potentially still reveal which data was downloaded.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] If this is a concern the Tor-based schemes mentioned further below might be a suitable alternative.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The mirror scheme specifies the location of a mirrorlist.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The file scheme allows an arbitrary directory in the file system to be considered an archive.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] This is useful for NFS mounts and local mirrors or archives.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The cdrom scheme allows APT to use a local CD-ROM, DVD or USB drive with media swapping.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] program to create cdrom entries in the source list.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The ftp scheme specifies an FTP server for an archive.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Use of FTP is on the decline in favour of http and https and many archives either never offered or are retiring FTP access.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Please note that an FTP proxy can be specified by using the **ftp_proxy** environment variable.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] It is possible to specify an HTTP proxy (HTTP proxy servers often understand FTP URLs) using this environment variable and *only* this environment variable.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Proxies using HTTP specified in the configuration file will be ignored.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The copy scheme is identical to the file scheme except that packages are copied into the cache directory instead of used directly at their location.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] This is useful for people using removable media to copy files around with APT.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The rsh/ssh method invokes RSH/SSH to connect to a remote host and access the files as a given user.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Prior configuration of rhosts or RSA keys is recommended.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] commands are used to perform the file transfers from the remote host.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] For instance, the APT team also maintains the package apt-transport-tor, which provides access methods for HTTP and HTTPS URIs routed via the Tor network.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Uses the archive stored locally (or NFS mounted) at /home/apt/debian for stable/main, stable/contrib, stable/non-free and stable/non-free-firmware.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] As above, except this uses the unstable (development) distribution.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] The first line gets package information for the architectures in APT::Architectures while the second always retrieves amd64 and armel.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Uses HTTP to access the archive at archive.debian.org, and uses only the hamm/main area.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Uses FTP to access the archive at ftp.debian.org, under the debian directory, and uses only the bookworm/contrib area.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Uses FTP to access the archive at ftp.debian.org, under the debian directory, and uses only the unstable/contrib area.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] If this line appears as well as the one in the previous example in sources.list a single FTP session will be used for both resource lines.
[src:apt-package/sources-list-5-en] Uses HTTP to get binary packages as well as sources from the stable, testing and unstable suites and the components main and contrib.
